03871nam a22004815i 9780228007630DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280076307 a10.1515/97802280076302doi  a(DE-B1597)657643  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR888.P6bP47 2021 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.9140935812231 aPerkin, J. Russell, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics and the British Novel in the 1970s /cJ. Russell Perkin. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tChronology -- tPolitics and the British Novel in the 1970s -- tIntroduction -- tThe Fiction of Discontent: Margaret Drabble’s The Ice Age and John fowles’s -- t“England made me”: John le Carré’s Karla trilogy -- tThe Green World of Richard Adams -- tThe Campus Novels of Malcolm Bradbury and David Lodge: Politics in a Small World -- tDoris Lessing’s feminist Apocalyptic -- tCamels on the Embankment: v.S. Naipaul and the Globalization of the Novel -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1970s in Britain saw a series of industrial disputes, a referendum on membership in the European Economic Community, conflict about issues of immigration and citizenship, and emergent environmental and feminist movements. It was also a decade of innovation in the novel, and novelists often addressed the state of the nation directly in their works.In Politics and the British Novel in the 1970s Russell Perkin looks at social novels by John Fowles and Margaret Drabble, the Cold War thrillers of John le Carré, Richard Adams's best-selling fable Watership Down, the popular campus novels of Malcolm Bradbury and David Lodge, Doris Lessing's dystopian visions, and V.S. Naipaul's explorations of post-colonial displacement. Many of these highly regarded works sold in large numbers and have enjoyed enduring success – a testament to the power of the political novel to explain a nation to itself. Perkin explores the connections between the novel and politics, situating the works it discusses in the rich context of the history and culture of the decade, from party politics to popular television shows.Politics and the British Novel in the 1970s elucidates a period of literary history now fifty years in the past and offers a balanced perspective on the age, revealing that these works not only represented the politics of the time but played a meaningful role in them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitical fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreat Britain. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228007630?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228007630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228007630/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles